      "number": 19,
      "title": "19",
      "speaker_notes": "WIP\nTicket Distribution: P1/P2 tickets expected to be ~10\u201315%, while P3/P4 tickets will constitute ~85\u201390% of the overall volume.\nIntegration Mix: Assumes ~50% real-time and 50% batch integrations, with an estimated ~5% retry/failure rate within standard thresholds.\nStakeholder Availability: All relevant functional and business stakeholders will be available during the discovery phase (Phase 1) for requirements validation and alignment.\nActual resource count may be adjusted based on:\nTicket volume variation beyond \u00b110% of baseline assumptions\nChange in the number or complexity of integrations compared to the RFP scope\nCOLA (Cost of Living Adjustment) as applicable\nProductivity improvements / efficiency gains over the engagement lifecycle\nA production-replica (non-production) environment will be available to simulate, troubleshoot, and recreate production issues without impacting live operations\n\nSLAs, access, and dependencies on OEM (Oracle) remain as per standard cloud support model\nTimely access to systems, data, and client SMEs is assumed for issue resolution\nAssumes no prior ticket history is available; initial estimates are based on standard industry benchmarks and may vary post-transition\nAssumes no major undocumented or highly customized business workflows exist beyond standard Salesforce/CPQ capabilities\nStability and supportability of third-party integrations (if any) are assumed; delays/issues from external vendors are out of scope\nTimely access to all environments (Prod, UAT, Sandbox), tools, and documentation is assumed for smooth transition and support.\nAssumes enhancement/change requests remain within agreed baseline; significant deviations may require scope and effort reassessment.\nAssumes a defined release management process exists; absence may lead to higher defect leakage and support effort.\nAssumes data volumes are within platform limits and no major archival/cleanup is required during transition.\nAny additional compliance, audit, or security requirements (beyond standard Salesforce controls) may impact delivery timelines.\nAssumes end users are adequately trained; low adoption or incorrect usage may increase ticket volume (especially P3/P4).\nAssumes pricing rules, product configurations, and approval matrices are documented; otherwise, additional discovery effort will be required.\nAssumes existing integrations have defined retry/error-handling mechanisms; absence may increase manual intervention.",
